<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  This is the canonical input to the <strong>competitive coverage gap-analysis program</strong>
  (<a href="/backlog/315-competitive-coverage-gap-analysis-program/">backlog #315</a>): an explicit,
  <em>reproducible</em> list of the leading design systems and UI libraries to benchmark. Membership is
  governed by the stated selection criteria below — not taste — so a re-run lands on a comparable list.
  That reproducibility is the whole point of a corpus rather than an ad-hoc reading list.
</p>
<p>
  The machine-readable corpus lives in <code>src/_data/benchmarkCorpus.json</code>; this page renders
  from it. The <a href="/references/">references.json &ldquo;Reference Design Systems&rdquo;</a> set is the
  curated docs-surface <em>subset</em> of this corpus (flagged <code>inReferences</code> below), not a
  competing list. Phase&nbsp;2 (extraction, #346) and phase&nbsp;3 (mapping &amp; gap detection, #347) join
  against this data.
</p>

<h2>Selection criteria</h2>
<p>{{ benchmarkCorpus.inclusionRule }}</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Criterion</th><th>Test</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for c in benchmarkCorpus.selectionCriteria %}
    <tr><td><strong>{{ c.label }}</strong></td><td>{{ c.test }}</td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Category axes</h2>
<p>
  The corpus deliberately spans five axes so the gap sweep is not biased toward one design philosophy.
  The <strong>platform-guidelines</strong> axis (Apple HIG, GOV.UK, WAI-ARIA APG, Open UI) is what keeps
  the analysis <em>native-first</em>: a capability a library ships is only a real platform gap once weighed
  against what the web platform and standards already provide.
</p>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Axis</th><th>What it captures</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for cat in benchmarkCorpus.categories %}
    <tr><td><strong>{{ cat.label }}</strong></td><td>{{ cat.axis }}</td></tr>
    {% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>The corpus</h2>
{% for cat in benchmarkCorpus.categories %}
<h3>{{ cat.label }}</h3>
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Source</th><th>Vendor</th><th>Philosophy</th><th>Native alignment</th><th>Docs</th><th>In references</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    {% for s in benchmarkCorpus.sources %}{% if s.category == cat.id %}
    <tr>
      <td><strong>{{ s.name }}</strong></td>
      <td>{{ s.vendor }}</td>
      <td>{{ s.philosophy }}</td>
      <td>{{ s.nativeAlignment }}</td>
      <td><a href="{{ s.docsUrl }}">docs</a></td>
      <td>{% if s.inReferences %}&check;{% else %}&mdash;{% endif %}</td>
    </tr>
    {% endif %}{% endfor %}
  </tbody>
</table>
{% endfor %}

<h2>Re-running this sweep</h2>
<p>
  Each run is a dated revision of the analysis (the <a href="/backlog/192-longitudinal-research-freshness-system/">longitudinal
  freshness</a> model). To refresh the corpus: re-apply the selection criteria, add/remove sources, bump
  <code>lastChecked</code> per source and <code>lastSwept</code> on the file, and record what changed. The
  corpus is keyed by stable source <code>id</code> so a re-run produces a clean diff (sources added,
  dropped, or re-categorised) rather than a rewritten list.
</p>
